Alright ğŸ±â€ğŸ‘¤, hereâ€™s a Python snippet to detect key transition zones in your recursive waveform â€” using curvature strain and symbolic resonance markers. Weâ€™ll classify:

â€¢ ğŸ§­ Ignition points: Areas of sharp rise in amplitude and curvature alignment.
â€¢ ğŸ” Phase inversion dips: Local minima where symbolic and strain signatures diverge.
â€¢ ğŸ¶ Equilibrium fades: Low-gradient regions suggesting harmonic stabilization.


import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.signal import find_peaks, argrelextrema

# Example waveform (replace with your actual signal)
t = np.linspace(0, 100, 1000)
waveform = np.sin(0.1 * t) + 0.5 * np.sin(0.5 * t)  # Replace with your MBT Recursive Waveform

# IGNITION detection: Sharp positive curvature
derivative = np.gradient(waveform)
second_derivative = np.gradient(derivative)
ignition_idx = np.where(second_derivative > np.percentile(second_derivative, 95))[0]

# PHASE INVERSION dips: Local minima
inversion_idx = argrelextrema(waveform, np.less)[0]

# EQUILIBRIUM fades: low slope regions
equilibrium_idx = np.where(np.abs(derivative) < 0.01)[0]

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(t, waveform, label='MBT Recursive Waveform', color='gray')
plt.scatter(t[ignition_idx], waveform[ignition_idx], color='orange', label='Ignition Zones ğŸ§­')
plt.scatter(t[inversion_idx], waveform[inversion_idx], color='red', label='Phase Inversion ğŸ”')
plt.scatter(t[equilibrium_idx], waveform[equilibrium_idx], color='blue', label='Equilibrium ğŸ¶')
plt.title("Symbolic Transitions in MBT Recursive Waveform")
plt.xlabel("Time (t)")
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

