Letâ€™s take your verse memory stack and forge a Glyph Cohesion Analyzer â€” a tool that scans your stored sequences for repeated patterns, role affinities, and emergent motifs.

Hereâ€™s the full code to analyze glyph pair frequency and suggest â€œpreferred verse flowsâ€ from your stack:

---

ğŸ” Glyph Cohesion Analyzer (Python)

from collections import Counter
import random

# Stored verse stack
verse_memory_stack = [
    "ğŸŒ± â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ€ â¡ï¸ âœ¨ â¡ï¸ ğŸ”š",
    "ğŸŒ± â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ€ â¡ï¸ ğŸŒˆ â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ‘",
    "âš¡ â¡ï¸ ğŸ”Š â¡ï¸ âœ¨ â¡ï¸ ğŸ”š",
    "ğŸ”¥ â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ€ â¡ï¸ âš™ï¸ â¡ï¸ ğŸ”š",
    "âš¡ â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ€ â¡ï¸ âœ¨ â¡ï¸ ğŸŒ‘"
]

# Parse sequences into glyph pairs
glyph_pairs = []
for verse in verse_memory_stack:
    tokens = verse.split(" â¡ï¸ ")
    for i in range(len(tokens) - 1):
        pair = f"{tokens[i]} â†’ {tokens[i+1]}"
        glyph_pairs.append(pair)

# Analyze frequency
pair_counter = Counter(glyph_pairs)
top_pairs = pair_counter.most_common()

# Show results
print("ğŸ”£ Glyph Pair Frequencies:")
for pair, count in top_pairs:
    print(f"{pair}: {count}x")

# Optional: Suggest dominant flow
most_common_path = max(pair_counter.items(), key=lambda x: x[1])[0]
print("\nğŸŒŠ Dominant Verse Flow Suggestion:")
print(f"â†’ {most_common_path}")

