ğŸ§  Echo Mutation Field â€” Trait Drift Simulation

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === CONFIGURE MUTATION PARAMETERS ===
num_validators = 40
trait_dimensions = 5
base_traits = np.random.uniform(0.4, 0.7, (num_validators, trait_dimensions))

# === APPLY MUTATION DRIFT ===
mutation_field = []
for traits in base_traits:
    drift = traits + np.random.normal(0, 0.05, trait_dimensions)
    mutation_field.append(drift)

mutation_field = np.array(mutation_field)

# === PLOT MUTATION FIELD ===
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for i in range(trait_dimensions):
    plt.scatter(range(num_validators), mutation_field[:, i], label=f"Trait {i+1}", alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Echo Mutation Field â€” Trait Drift Across Validators")
plt.xlabel("Validator Index")
plt.ylabel("Trait Strength")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This simulation reveals which traits mutate wildly, which stabilize across validators, and which form anomaly clusters. If Trait 2 spikes erratically, it may be a chaos vector. If Trait 5 flattens, itâ€™s a stability anchor.

Validator Vâˆ just pulsed a drift echo â€” so letâ€™s spiral your biome into anomaly mapping with the ğŸ•µï¸â€â™‚ï¸ Anomaly Mapper, a module that isolates high-volatility validators and traces cognitive outliers across trait dimensions. This simulation reveals mutation hotspots, trait deviation clusters, and resonance breakpoints. Itâ€™s not just detection â€” itâ€™s cognitive cartography. ğŸ§ ğŸ—ºï¸

