ğŸ§  Code: Principal Component Analyzer for Trait Space

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# === Load evolution log
df = pd.DataFrame(evolution_log)

# === Trait selection
traits = ["Echo Score", "Collapse Count", "Avg Curvature", "Avg Tension", "Phase Divergence", "Risk"]
X = df[traits]

# === Standardize traits before PCA
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# === Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)  # First two principal components
components = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# === Attach species labels
df['PC1'] = components[:, 0]
df['PC2'] = components[:, 1]

# === Plot PCA result
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
species_colors = {
    "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸": "dodgerblue",
    "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸": "darkgreen",
    "Entropy Nomad ğŸ§­": "crimson",
    "Rebound Rebel âš¡": "orange",
    "Echo Royalty ğŸ‘‘": "purple"
}
for species, group in df.groupby("Species"):
    plt.scatter(group["PC1"], group["PC2"], label=species, s=60, alpha=0.7,
                color=species_colors.get(species, "gray"), edgecolors='k')

plt.title("ğŸ§¬ Validator Trait Archetypes (PCA Reduction)", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1")
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

ğŸ” What Youâ€™re Looking For

â€¢ Tight species clusters = high trait fidelity
â€¢ Scatter zones = phenotype overlap or instability
â€¢ PC1 vs PC2 reveals core biome dynamics:â€¢ PC1 often aligns with survival axis (curvature, tension, collapse)
â€¢ PC2 captures divergence or echo chaos



If Echo Drifters form a tidy island and Survivors scatter wildly, it means validator physics favors specific attractor geometries.


Youâ€™re now visualizing evolution as multidimensional gravity. ğŸ“˜ğŸŒŒ Letâ€™s keep decoding what drives validator identity.


Validator migration flows, coming right up. ğŸŒğŸ§¬
This module traces how validators move through trait space across generations â€” showing whether species stay put, drift, or cross into new archetype territories.

Weâ€™ll plot arrows from each generationâ€™s centroid to the next in PCA space, revealing biome dynamics in motion.

---

ğŸ§­ Code: Evolutionary Flow Map in PCA Space

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# === Load and prepare data
df = pd.DataFrame(evolution_log)
traits = ["Echo Score", "Collapse Count", "Avg Curvature", "Avg Tension", "Phase Divergence", "Risk"]
X = df[traits]

# === Standardize traits
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# === Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
components = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)
df["PC1"] = components[:, 0]
df["PC2"] = components[:, 1]

# === Calculate generation centroids
centroids = df.groupby("Generation")[["PC1", "PC2"]].mean().reset_index()

# === Plot flow map
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(df["PC1"], df["PC2"], alpha=0.3, s=30, label="Validators", color="gray")

# Plot centroid points
plt.scatter(centroids["PC1"], centroids["PC2"], color="mediumvioletred", s=80, label="Gen Centroids", zorder=3)

# Plot arrows between centroids
for i in range(len(centroids) - 1):
    x1, y1 = centroids.loc[i, ["PC1", "PC2"]]
    x2, y2 = centroids.loc[i + 1, ["PC1", "PC2"]]
    plt.arrow(x1, y1, x2 - x1, y2 - y1, head_width=0.08, head_length=0.08,
              fc="mediumvioletred", ec="mediumvioletred", length_includes_head=True)

# === Styling
plt.title("ğŸ”„ Validator Trait Migration Across Generations", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1")
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

ğŸ” What Youâ€™ll See

â€¢ Arrows jumping far = biome turbulence, validators searching for survival
â€¢ Tight flow = trait stability, evolution favoring known niches
â€¢ Curve turns = biome redirection â€” validator identities shifting as pressure changes


If the flow spirals inward, itâ€™s trait gravity in action. If it drifts outward or loops, youâ€™re watching validator culture change.

---

ğŸ§­ Code: Validator Lineage Drift Tracker (PCA Paths)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# === Load and prepare data
df = pd.DataFrame(evolution_log)
traits = ["Echo Score", "Collapse Count", "Avg Curvature", "Avg Tension", "Phase Divergence", "Risk"]

# === Standardize and apply PCA
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df[traits])
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
components = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# === Attach PCA components back to DataFrame
df["PC1"] = components[:, 0]
df["PC2"] = components[:, 1]

# === Assign unique validator IDs (by order of appearance per generation)
df["Validator"] = df.groupby("Generation").cumcount() + 1

# === Plot migration lines
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
species_colors = {
    "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸": "dodgerblue",
    "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸": "darkgreen",
    "Entropy Nomad ğŸ§­": "crimson",
    "Rebound Rebel âš¡": "orange",
    "Echo Royalty ğŸ‘‘": "purple"
}

# Draw lines for each validator ID
for vid in df["Validator"].unique():
    track = df[df["Validator"] == vid].sort_values("Generation")
    if len(track) > 1:
        plt.plot(track["PC1"], track["PC2"], alpha=0.5, linewidth=2,
                 color=species_colors.get(track.iloc[-1]["Species"], "gray"))

# === Scatter points for clarity
for species, group in df.groupby("Species"):
    plt.scatter(group["PC1"], group["PC2"], s=60, alpha=0.7,
                label=species, color=species_colors.get(species, "gray"), edgecolors='k')

# === Final styling
plt.title("ğŸŒŒ Validator Trait Drift Across Generations", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Principal Component 1")
plt.ylabel("Principal Component 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

