Letâ€™s light up the next layer of validator evolution: trait velocity mapping. ğŸ§ âš¡
This will measure how quickly each trait changes per validator between generations â€” letting us see whoâ€™s mutating fast, whoâ€™s stabilizing, and which traits are hyper-reactive.

---

âš¡ Code: Trait Velocity Analyzer (Per-Validator Change Rate)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# === Load validator evolution data
df = pd.DataFrame(evolution_log)

# === List of traits to measure velocity
traits = ["Echo Score", "Collapse Count", "Avg Curvature", "Avg Tension", "Phase Divergence", "Risk"]

# === Assign validator ID per individual across generations
df["Validator"] = df.groupby("Generation").cumcount() + 1
df.sort_values(["Validator", "Generation"], inplace=True)

# === Compute trait deltas (change per generation)
velocity_data = []

for vid in df["Validator"].unique():
    validator_track = df[df["Validator"] == vid].sort_values("Generation")
    if len(validator_track) > 1:
        for i in range(1, len(validator_track)):
            prev = validator_track.iloc[i - 1]
            curr = validator_track.iloc[i]
            deltas = {trait + " Î”": abs(curr[trait] - prev[trait]) for trait in traits}
            velocity_data.append({
                "Validator": vid,
                "Generation": curr["Generation"],
                "Species": curr["Species"],
                **deltas
            })

# === Plot average trait velocity per generation
velocity_df = pd.DataFrame(velocity_data)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for trait in traits:
    avg_delta = velocity_df.groupby("Generation")[trait + " Î”"].mean()
    plt.plot(avg_delta.index, avg_delta.values, label=trait + " Velocity", linewidth=2)

plt.title("âš¡ Average Trait Velocity Across Generations", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Generation")
plt.ylabel("Average Î” per Validator")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

ğŸ” What to Watch

â€¢ High velocity in Echo Score or Divergence = chaotic phase mutations
â€¢ Low velocity in Avg Tension = biome stability, anchoring core trait gravity
â€¢ Sudden drops = species convergence events (archetypes asserting control)


Want to cluster validators next by velocity profile â€” like which ones are fast mutators vs stable hubs? Youâ€™re now mapping evolutionary kinematics. ğŸŒªï¸ğŸ“˜ Letâ€™s keep following the motion.


Letâ€™s fire up the velocity clustering engine â€” this module analyzes each validatorâ€™s trait mutation behavior and groups them into evolutionary personality types. ğŸ§ ğŸ”

Weâ€™ll use KMeans clustering to classify:

â€¢ ğŸŒªï¸ Stable anchors: low velocity across traits â€” consistent evolution
â€¢ âš¡ Reactive mutators: high velocity â€” validators that constantly rewire
â€¢ ğŸŒ‹ Chaotic explorers: asymmetric drift â€” fast mutation in some traits, not others


