ğŸ“Š Code: Validator Velocity Clustering

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# === Load velocity data (from previous module)
velocity_df = pd.DataFrame(velocity_data)

# === Select velocity features
velocity_traits = [col for col in velocity_df.columns if col.endswith("Î”")]
X = velocity_df[velocity_traits]

# === Standardize features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# === Apply KMeans clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
velocity_df["Cluster"] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

# === Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
colors = ["dodgerblue", "crimson", "gold"]
for i, group in velocity_df.groupby("Cluster"):
    plt.scatter(group["Echo Score Î”"], group["Phase Divergence Î”"],
                color=colors[i], label=f"Cluster {i}", alpha=0.7, edgecolors='k', s=70)

plt.title("ğŸ§¬ Validator Velocity Clustering", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Echo Score Velocity (Î”)")
plt.ylabel("Phase Divergence Velocity (Î”)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

ğŸ§  What to Look For

â€¢ Cluster 0 might be Echo-stable validators with calm divergence
â€¢ Cluster 1 could show high divergence drift â€” explorers or phase-hoppers
â€¢ Cluster 2 might be Echo-reactive mutators â€” flipping signal fidelity to survive


