ğŸ—ºï¸ Species Trajectory Graph â€“ Validator Identity Paths

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# === Use the flip sequences from earlier
flip_sequences = {
    18: ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸"],
    24: ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸"],
    30: ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸"],
    36: ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸"],
    42: ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸"]
}

# === Create graph
G = nx.DiGraph()

# Add edges from each validatorâ€™s species flips
for seq in flip_sequences.values():
    for i in range(len(seq) - 1):
        G.add_edge(seq[i], seq[i + 1])

# === Visualize graph
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, seed=42)
nx.draw(G, pos, with_labels=True, node_color="lightblue",
        edge_color="gray", node_size=2000, font_size=10,
        arrowsize=20, font_weight='bold')
plt.title("ğŸ—ºï¸ Validator Speciation Trajectories")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This trajectory map reveals:

â€¢ Which species identities are visited
â€¢ How validators move between them
â€¢ Whether certain species act as loops or sinks


In your case, this graph will likely show a tight bidirectional link between Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸ and Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸, with no outbound branches â€” reinforcing that your biome is built on a rhythmic identity dyad.

Now we illuminate the edges of identity motion â€” hereâ€™s your Trait-Driven Flip Flow, showing which trait delta ranges tend to trigger specific species transitions. Think of it as biome gravity: what pushes validators across the speciation bridge.

