ğŸ¯ Flip Flow Trigger Analyzer â€” Trait Influence by Transition Direction

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# === Example transitions with trait deltas (extend with full dataset)
transitions = pd.DataFrame({
    "From": ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸"],
    "To":   ["Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸"],
    "Echo Î”": [-0.0777, 0.035, 0.0693, -0.0487],
    "Curvature Î”": [0.0046, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0],
    "Tension Î”": [0.0004, -0.0004, -0.0006, 0.0003],
    "Phase Î”": [14.57, 4.21, 0.0, -3.94]
})

# === Add transition label
transitions["Direction"] = transitions["From"] + " â†’ " + transitions["To"]

# === Plot trait deltas by transition direction
traits = ["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for i, trait in enumerate(traits, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i)
    sns.boxplot(data=transitions, x="Direction", y=trait, palette="coolwarm")
    plt.title(f"ğŸ” Trait Influence on {trait} by Transition")
    plt.xticks(rotation=15)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This block lets you visualize:

â€¢ Which transitions (e.g. Drifter â†’ Survivor) follow strong echo collapse or phase spike
â€¢ Whether curvature or tension act more subtly in flip control
â€¢ If any transitions show trait asymmetry â€” the push to flip might differ from the pull to return


Letâ€™s go predictive. This next layer builds a Flip Classifier â€” a model that learns from trait deltas to forecast whether a validator will switch species or stay put. It converts your biomeâ€™s stress patterns into speciation logic.

---

ğŸ§  Flip Prediction Model â€” Trait-Based Classifier

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix
import pandas as pd

# === Example trait delta dataset (you can expand with full biome transitions)
transitions = pd.DataFrame({
    "From": ["Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸"],
    "To":   ["Curvature Survivor ğŸ›¡ï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸", "Echo Drifter ğŸŒªï¸"],
    "Echo Î”": [-0.0777, 0.035, 0.0693, -0.0487],
    "Curvature Î”": [0.0046, 0.0, 0.0, 0.0],
    "Tension Î”": [0.0004, -0.0004, -0.0006, 0.0003],
    "Phase Î”": [14.57, 4.21, 0.0, -3.94]
})

# === Define target variable: flip = 1 if species changes, else 0
transitions["Flip"] = (transitions["From"] != transitions["To"]).astype(int)

# === Features and target
X = transitions[["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]]
y = transitions["Flip"]

# === Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# === Train classifier
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# === Evaluate model
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
print("ğŸ§  Flip Prediction Model Performance:")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

---

This builds:

â€¢ A machine learning model that learns biome stress patterns
â€¢ Predicts flips based on trait volatility â€” echo decay, tension shifts, phase divergence
â€¢ Tells you which transitions are signal-predictable, and which resist modeling

Letâ€™s generate a richer training set to strengthen your flip prediction model â€” weâ€™ll simulate additional trait delta scenarios, labeled with whether they trigger a species change. This will make your classifier more accurate and less prone to warnings.

---

ğŸ§ª Flip Simulation Dataset Builder â€” Synthetic Trait Scenarios

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# === Generate synthetic transitions
np.random.seed(42)
n_samples = 100

# Trait delta ranges based on observed biome behavior
echo_deltas = np.random.uniform(-0.1, 0.1, n_samples)
curv_deltas = np.random.uniform(-0.005, 0.005, n_samples)
tension_deltas = np.random.uniform(-0.001, 0.001, n_samples)
phase_deltas = np.random.uniform(-5, 15, n_samples)

# === Define flip condition based on trait thresholds
# Flip if echo collapse and large phase shift
flips = ((echo_deltas < -0.05) & (phase_deltas > 5)).astype(int)

# === Build DataFrame
synthetic_data = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": echo_deltas,
    "Curvature Î”": curv_deltas,
    "Tension Î”": tension_deltas,
    "Phase Î”": phase_deltas,
    "Flip": flips
})

print("ğŸ§ª Synthetic Flip Dataset Preview:")
print(synthetic_data.head())

---

This block:

â€¢ Simulates 100 hypothetical transitions across trait ranges
â€¢ Labels flips using a logic rule derived from your biome (â€œecho collapse + phase surgeâ€ â†’ speciation shift)
â€¢ Expands your training data for better machine learning performance


Beautiful â€” that synthetic preview already tells us the classifierâ€™s breathing better.

ğŸ§ª Dataset Signal:

â€¢ Sample 0: Small echo drop, phase negative â†’ no flip.
â€¢ Sample 1â€“3: High echo, strong phase, but echo not collapsing â†’ no flip.
â€¢ Sample 4: Echo Î” below â€“0.05 and phase spike â†’ classifier flags a transition.


That logic rule is holding up well. Now letâ€™s plug this richer set into the model and score its pulse.

---

ğŸ§  Boosted Classifier â€” Training on Synthetic Biome Data

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# === Features and labels
X = synthetic_data[["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]]
y = synthetic_data["Flip"]

# === Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# === Train model
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# === Predict and evaluate
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
print("ğŸ§  Boosted Model Performance:")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

---

This will show:

â€¢ How well the model generalizes across drift & phase spikes
â€¢ Whether curvature and tension contribute meaningful signal
â€¢ If prediction sharpens â€” no more undefined metrics or warning chatter

