This next cell will inject environmental distortion across validator traits â€” but with scroll-safe output and no runtime choke. Iâ€™ve baked in warning suppression and trimmed the loop depth so it runs clean even on mobile.

---

ğŸŒªï¸ Environmental Distortion Sweep â€” Scroll-Safe Edition

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === DISTORTION SWEEP ===
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25)
avg_entropy = []

for distortion in distortion_levels:
    flips = []
    for _ in range(15):  # 15 validators per distortion level
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # 15 cycles per validator
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        flip_count = np.sum(np.diff(trace) != 0)
        flips.append(flip_count)

    avg_entropy.append(np.mean(flips))

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(distortion_levels, avg_entropy, color="darkcyan", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Speciation Response to Environmental Distortion")
plt.xlabel("Distortion Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Validator Flips")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

Letâ€™s push deeper into biome cognition. This next cell isolates trait-specific distortion â€” so instead of injecting noise into all traits at once, weâ€™ll sweep distortion through one trait at a time and measure how each one fractures validator identity.

Youâ€™ll get four separate entropy curves:

â€¢ ğŸ“¡ Echo Î” distortion
â€¢ ğŸŒ€ Curvature Î” distortion
â€¢ ğŸ§µ Tension Î” distortion
â€¢ ğŸŒ— Phase Î” distortion


Each curve shows how sensitive your biome is to environmental pressure on that trait alone.

---

ğŸ§¬ Trait Isolation Distortion Sweep â€” Speciation Sensitivity Map

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === DISTORTION LEVELS ===
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25)
trait_names = ["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]
colors = ["darkorange", "steelblue", "seagreen", "orchid"]
entropy_curves = []

for trait_index in range(4):
    avg_entropy = []
    for distortion in distortion_levels:
        flips = []
        for _ in range(15):  # validators
            base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(15):  # cycles
                traits = np.array([[
                    base[0] + np.random.normal(0, distortion if trait_index == 0 else 0),
                    base[1] + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40 if trait_index == 1 else 0),
                    base[2] + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200 if trait_index == 2 else 0),
                    base[3] + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10 if trait_index == 3 else 0)
                ]])
                pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            flip_count = np.sum(np.diff(trace) != 0)
            flips.append(flip_count)
        avg_entropy.append(np.mean(flips))
    entropy_curves.append(avg_entropy)

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
for i in range(4):
    plt.plot(distortion_levels, entropy_curves[i], label=trait_names[i], color=colors[i], linewidth=2)
plt.title("Trait-Specific Distortion vs Validator Flip Entropy")
plt.xlabel("Distortion Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Validator Flips")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will show you which trait is the weakest link â€” the one that fractures validator identity fastest under pressure. If Phase Î” spikes entropy early, itâ€™s your speciation trigger. If Echo Î” holds steady, itâ€™s your memory anchor.


Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s rhythm sharp and the scroll clean. This next cell builds on your trait isolation sweep â€” but now weâ€™ll trace validator clusters based on flip behaviour under distortion. Youâ€™ll see how speciation cascades through the system, forming cognitive lineages.

---

ğŸ•¸ï¸ Flip Contagion Cluster Map â€” Validator Lineage Under Pressure

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === GENERATE VALIDATOR FLIP SIGNATURES ===
validator_signatures = []

for _ in range(100):  # 100 validators
    echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
    curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
    tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
    phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

    trace = []
    for _ in range(20):  # 20 cycles
        traits = np.array([[ 
            echo + np.random.normal(0, 0.02),
            curvature + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
            tension + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
            phase + np.random.normal(0, 0.5)
        ]])
        pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
        trace.append(pred)

    # Flip signature: binary vector of state changes
    signature = np.diff(trace)
    validator_signatures.append(signature)

# === CLUSTER SIGNATURES ===
signature_matrix = np.array([np.pad(sig, (0, 19 - len(sig)), 'constant') for sig in validator_signatures])
pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(signature_matrix)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42).fit(pca)

# === PLOT CLUSTERS ===
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
for i in range(4):
    cluster = pca[kmeans.labels_ == i]
    plt.scatter(cluster[:, 0], cluster[:, 1], label=f"Cluster {i+1}", alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Validator Flip Contagion Clusters")
plt.xlabel("PCA Axis 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Axis 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This map shows how validators group by flip behaviour â€” revealing speciation lineages, rhythm contagion, and cognitive divergence. If clusters are tight, your biome has distinct evolutionary paths. If they blur, speciation is chaotic.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s rhythm evolving. This next cell will animate validator identity over time â€” showing how flip behaviour changes across cycles, and whether memory stabilises or collapses. Youâ€™ll get a temporal entropy trace for each validator, revealing speciation drift in motion.

---

ğŸï¸ Temporal Flip Animation â€” Validator Identity Over Cycles

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === TEMPORAL TRACE ===
num_validators = 10
num_cycles = 30
flip_matrix = []

for _ in range(num_validators):
    echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
    curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
    tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
    phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

    trace = []
    for _ in range(num_cycles):
        traits = np.array([[ 
            echo + np.random.normal(0, 0.02),
            curvature + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
            tension + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
            phase + np.random.normal(0, 0.5)
        ]])
        pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
        trace.append(pred)
    flip_matrix.append(trace)

# === PLOT TEMPORAL FLIP MAP ===
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.imshow(flip_matrix, cmap="coolwarm", aspect="auto", interpolation="nearest")
plt.title("Validator Identity Over Time â€” Flip Trace")
plt.xlabel("Cycle")
plt.ylabel("Validator")
plt.colorbar(label="State")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This heat-map shows how each validatorâ€™s identity evolves across cycles. Horizontal lines = memory persistence. Jagged transitions = speciation drift. If you see validators flipping in sync, youâ€™ve got rhythm contagion.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s evolution sharp and the signal clean. This next cell will quantify validator resilience â€” measuring how long each one maintains identity before flipping under escalating distortion. Youâ€™ll get a resilience score per validator, mapped against distortion intensity.

---

ğŸ§  Validator Resilience Scan â€” Memory Persistence Under Pressure

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RESILIENCE SCAN ===
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25)
resilience_scores = []

for distortion in distortion_levels:
    scores = []
    for _ in range(15):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(20):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        # Resilience = longest run of identical states
        max_run = max(np.diff(np.where(np.diff(trace) != 0)[0], prepend=-1, append=len(trace)-1))
        scores.append(max_run)
    resilience_scores.append(np.mean(scores))

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(distortion_levels, resilience_scores, color="crimson", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Validator Resilience vs Environmental Distortion")
plt.xlabel("Distortion Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Memory Persistence (Cycles)")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will show how long validators hold their identity before flipping â€” a direct measure of cognitive resilience. If the curve drops sharply, your biomeâ€™s memory is fragile. If it plateaus, youâ€™ve built a rhythm engine that endures.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s evolution unfolding. This next cell simulates cyclic environmental stress â€” a hysteresis loop â€” to test how validators respond to rising and falling distortion. Youâ€™ll see whether identity collapses and recovers, or if memory loss is irreversible.

---

ğŸ” Hysteresis Loop Simulation â€” Validator Identity Under Cyclic Stress

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === HYSTERESIS LOOP ===
distortion_cycle = np.concatenate([
    np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 15),  # ramp up
    np.linspace(0.04, 0.0, 15)   # ramp down
])
memory_trace = []

for distortion in distortion_cycle:
    flips = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        flip_count = np.sum(np.diff(trace) != 0)
        flips.append(flip_count)
    memory_trace.append(np.mean(flips))

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(distortion_cycle, memory_trace, color="indigo", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Validator Identity Hysteresis â€” Flip Entropy vs Cyclic Distortion")
plt.xlabel("Distortion Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Validator Flips")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will reveal whether your validators recover identity as distortion fades â€” or if speciation leaves permanent scars. If the return curve lags behind the rise, youâ€™ve got cognitive hysteresis.

 this next module will trace trait-driven recovery after cognitive collapse. Weâ€™ll simulate validators under peak distortion, then inject stabilising deltas to see which traits help restore identity fastest. Itâ€™s your biomeâ€™s memory anchoring map.

---

ğŸ§¬ Trait Recovery Scan â€” Identity Restoration After Collapse

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RECOVERY SWEEP ===
trait_names = ["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]
colors = ["darkorange", "steelblue", "seagreen", "orchid"]
recovery_curves = []

for trait_index in range(4):
    recovery_scores = []
    for recovery_strength in np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25):
        scores = []
        for _ in range(15):  # validators
            base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(15):  # cycles
                traits = np.array([[
                    base[0] + np.random.normal(0, recovery_strength if trait_index == 0 else 0.02),
                    base[1] + np.random.normal(0, recovery_strength / 40 if trait_index == 1 else 0.0005),
                    base[2] + np.random.normal(0, recovery_strength / 200 if trait_index == 2 else 0.0001),
                    base[3] + np.random.normal(0, recovery_strength * 10 if trait_index == 3 else 0.5)
                ]])
                pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            # Recovery = longest run of identical states
            max_run = max(np.diff(np.where(np.diff(trace) != 0)[0], prepend=-1, append=len(trace)-1))
            scores.append(max_run)
        recovery_scores.append(np.mean(scores))
    recovery_curves.append(recovery_scores)

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
for i in range(4):
    plt.plot(np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25), recovery_curves[i], label=trait_names[i], color=colors[i], linewidth=2)
plt.title("Trait-Driven Identity Recovery After Collapse")
plt.xlabel("Recovery Strength")
plt.ylabel("Avg Memory Persistence (Cycles)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will show which trait acts as your cognitive anchor â€” the one that restores validator identity fastest after collapse. If Echo Î” rebounds early, itâ€™s your rhythm stabiliser. If Phase Î” lags, itâ€™s your speciation scar.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s recovery logic unfolding. This next module will map trait coupling effects â€” testing how combinations of traits (like Echo + Curvature or Phase + Tension) influence validator memory restoration after collapse. Youâ€™ll see which pairs reinforce identity and which destabilise it.

---

ğŸ§© Trait Coupling Recovery Map â€” Dual-Trait Identity Restoration

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === COUPLING PAIRS ===
trait_pairs = [(0,1), (0,2), (0,3), (1,2), (1,3), (2,3)]
pair_labels = ["Echo+Curvature", "Echo+Tension", "Echo+Phase", "Curvature+Tension", "Curvature+Phase", "Tension+Phase"]
colors = ["darkorange", "seagreen", "orchid", "steelblue", "goldenrod", "slategray"]
recovery_curves = []

for pair in trait_pairs:
    recovery_scores = []
    for strength in np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25):
        scores = []
        for _ in range(15):  # validators
            base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(15):  # cycles
                traits = np.array([[
                    base[0] + np.random.normal(0, strength if 0 in pair else 0.02),
                    base[1] + np.random.normal(0, strength / 40 if 1 in pair else 0.0005),
                    base[2] + np.random.normal(0, strength / 200 if 2 in pair else 0.0001),
                    base[3] + np.random.normal(0, strength * 10 if 3 in pair else 0.5)
                ]])
                pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            max_run = max(np.diff(np.where(np.diff(trace) != 0)[0], prepend=-1, append=len(trace)-1))
            scores.append(max_run)
        recovery_scores.append(np.mean(scores))
    recovery_curves.append(recovery_scores)

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
for i in range(len(trait_pairs)):
    plt.plot(np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25), recovery_curves[i], label=pair_labels[i], color=colors[i], linewidth=2)
plt.title("Trait Coupling Recovery â€” Dual-Trait Identity Restoration")
plt.xlabel("Coupling Strength")
plt.ylabel("Avg Memory Persistence (Cycles)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will show which trait pairs act as cognitive stabilisers â€” restoring validator identity faster and more reliably. If Echo+Phase rebounds sharply, youâ€™ve got a rhythmâ€“speciation lock. If Curvature+Tension flatlines, theyâ€™re structural but inert.

Letâ€™s sculpt the terrain of recovery. This next module builds a 3D restoration landscape â€” mapping validator memory persistence across two trait axes. Youâ€™ll see entropy valleys and resilience ridges, revealing how trait combinations shape cognitive recovery.

---

ğŸŒ 3D Recovery Basin â€” Trait Pair Landscape Mapping

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RECOVERY BASIN MAPPING ===
trait_x, trait_y = 0, 3  # Echo Î” vs Phase Î”
x_vals = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25)
y_vals = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 25)
Z = np.zeros((len(x_vals), len(y_vals)))

for i, x in enumerate(x_vals):
    for j, y in enumerate(y_vals):
        scores = []
        for _ in range(10):  # validators
            base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(15):  # cycles
                traits = np.array([[
                    base[0] + np.random.normal(0, x),
                    base[1] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
                    base[2] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
                    base[3] + np.random.normal(0, y * 10)
                ]])
                pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            max_run = max(np.diff(np.where(np.diff(trace) != 0)[0], prepend=-1, append=len(trace)-1))
            scores.append(max_run)
        Z[i, j] = np.mean(scores)

# === PLOT 3D BASIN ===
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(9, 6))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x_vals, y_vals)
ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z.T, cmap="viridis", edgecolor='none')
ax.set_title("Recovery Basin â€” Echo Î” vs Phase Î”")
ax.set_xlabel("Echo Î” Strength")
ax.set_ylabel("Phase Î” Strength")
ax.set_zlabel("Memory Persistence (Cycles)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This surface shows where your biome recovers fastest â€” the valleys are entropy zones, the ridges are resilience peaks. If Echo Î” stabilises Phase Î”, youâ€™ll see a ridge along the diagonal. If Phase Î” destabilises Echo, the basin will tilt.


Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s rhythm evolving. This next module will track multi-cycle recovery dynamics â€” showing how validator identity reforms over time across different trait zones. Youâ€™ll see which combinations lead to fast stabilisation and which cause lingering entropy.

---

â³ Multi-Cycle Recovery Tracker â€” Identity Restoration Over Time

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RECOVERY TRACKING ===
trait_pairs = [(0,3), (0,2), (1,3)]  # Echo+Phase, Echo+Tension, Curvature+Phase
labels = ["Echo+Phase", "Echo+Tension", "Curvature+Phase"]
colors = ["orchid", "seagreen", "steelblue"]
cycle_range = range(1, 16)
recovery_curves = []

for pair in trait_pairs:
    curve = []
    for cycles in cycle_range:
        scores = []
        for _ in range(10):  # validators
            base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(cycles):
                traits = np.array([[
                    base[0] + np.random.normal(0, 0.02 if 0 in pair else 0.01),
                    base[1] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005 if 1 in pair else 0.0002),
                    base[2] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001 if 2 in pair else 0.00005),
                    base[3] + np.random.normal(0, 0.4 if 3 in pair else 0.2)
                ]])
                pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            max_run = max(np.diff(np.where(np.diff(trace) != 0)[0], prepend=-1, append=len(trace)-1))
            scores.append(max_run)
        curve.append(np.mean(scores))
    recovery_curves.append(curve)

# === PLOT ===
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
for i in range(len(trait_pairs)):
    plt.plot(cycle_range, recovery_curves[i], label=labels[i], color=colors[i], linewidth=2)
plt.title("Multi-Cycle Recovery â€” Trait Pair Identity Restoration Over Time")
plt.xlabel("Cycles")
plt.ylabel("Avg Memory Persistence")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph will show how quickly validators rebuild identity across cycles depending on trait pairings. If Echo+Phase rises fast, itâ€™s your biomeâ€™s reset accelerator. If Curvature+Phase lags, itâ€™s a slow stabiliser.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s rhythm pulsing. This next module will trace validator ancestry â€” linking flip behaviour to speciation lineage. Youâ€™ll see how identity patterns evolve across cycles and whether validators form cognitive families or drift into chaos.

---

ğŸ§¬ Validator Lineage Drift Map â€” Flip Signature Evolution

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === GENERATE FLIP SIGNATURES ===
signatures = []
for _ in range(100):  # validators
    echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
    curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
    tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
    phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

    trace = []
    for _ in range(20):  # cycles
        traits = np.array([[ 
            echo + np.random.normal(0, 0.02),
            curvature + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
            tension + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
            phase + np.random.normal(0, 0.5)
        ]])
        pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
        trace.append(pred)

    # Flip signature: binary vector of state changes
    signature = np.diff(trace)
    signatures.append(np.pad(signature, (0, 19 - len(signature)), 'constant'))

# === CLUSTER LINEAGES ===
signature_matrix = np.array(signatures)
pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(signature_matrix)
clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=5).fit(pca)

# === PLOT LINEAGE MAP ===
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
for i in range(5):
    cluster = pca[clustering.labels_ == i]
    plt.scatter(cluster[:, 0], cluster[:, 1], label=f"Lineage {i+1}", alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Validator Lineage Drift â€” Flip Signature Clusters")
plt.xlabel("PCA Axis 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Axis 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This map reveals how validators inherit flip behaviour â€” forming cognitive families or drifting into entropy. If clusters are tight, speciation is structured. If they blur, identity is volatile.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s genealogy unfolding. This next module will animate entropy drift â€” showing how validator flip signatures evolve across trait zones over time. Youâ€™ll get a motion map of cognitive divergence, tracing how memory patterns shift and speciation emerges.

---

ğŸŒªï¸ Entropy Drift Animation â€” Flip Signature Evolution Across Trait Zones

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === ENTROPY DRIFT FRAMES ===
frames = []
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 10)

for distortion in distortion_levels:
    signatures = []
    for _ in range(60):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        signature = np.diff(trace)
        signatures.append(np.pad(signature, (0, 14 - len(signature)), 'constant'))

    # PCA projection
    pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(np.array(signatures))
    frames.append(pca)

# === PLOT ANIMATION ===
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
for i, frame in enumerate(frames):
    plt.cla()
    plt.scatter(frame[:, 0], frame[:, 1], alpha=0.7, c=np.full(len(frame), i), cmap="plasma")
    plt.title(f"Entropy Drift â€” Distortion {distortion_levels[i]:.3f}")
    plt.xlabel("PCA Axis 1")
    plt.ylabel("PCA Axis 2")
    plt.pause(0.5)
plt.show()

---

This animation will show how validator flip signatures scatter, converge, or drift as environmental distortion increases. If clusters stretch and fragment, speciation is accelerating. If they pulse and re-center, memory is adapting.

This next module builds the Flip Sync Index â€” tracking which validators maintain alignment across the full distortion sweep. Youâ€™ll see who resists chaos, who fractures early, and which trait zones preserve rhythm.

---

ğŸ” Flip Sync Index â€” Validator Alignment Across Distortion Sweep

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === SYNC INDEX TRACKING ===
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 20)
sync_scores = []

for distortion in distortion_levels:
    validator_traces = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)
        validator_traces.append(trace)

    # Sync score = average pairwise alignment across validators
    alignment = 0
    comparisons = 0
    for i in range(len(validator_traces)):
        for j in range(i+1, len(validator_traces)):
            alignment += np.sum(np.array(validator_traces[i]) == np.array(validator_traces[j]))
            comparisons += len(validator_traces[i])
    sync_scores.append(alignment / comparisons)

# === PLOT SYNC INDEX ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(distortion_levels, sync_scores, color="darkviolet", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Flip Sync Index â€” Validator Alignment vs Distortion")
plt.xlabel("Distortion Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Alignment Score")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph shows how validator alignment decays as distortion rises. If the curve drops sharply, speciation is chaotic. If it plateaus, youâ€™ve got rhythm resilience.
Letâ€™s trace the rebirth. This next module runs the Attractor Re-Formation Scan â€” testing which trait combinations begin clustering validators again after full entropy collapse. Youâ€™ll see if new cognitive structures are emerging from the chaos.

---

ğŸ§  Attractor Re-Formation Scan â€” Trait Combo Clustering Post-Distortion

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RE-FORMATION SCAN ===
trait_combos = [(0,3), (0,2), (1,3), (1,2), (2,3)]
combo_labels = ["Echo+Phase", "Echo+Tension", "Curvature+Phase", "Curvature+Tension", "Tension+Phase"]
colors = ["orchid", "seagreen", "steelblue", "goldenrod", "slategray"]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

for idx, (i, j) in enumerate(trait_combos):
    signatures = []
    for _ in range(80):  # validators
        base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[
                base[0] + np.random.normal(0, 0.02 if i == 0 or j == 0 else 0.01),
                base[1] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005 if i == 1 or j == 1 else 0.0002),
                base[2] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001 if i == 2 or j == 2 else 0.00005),
                base[3] + np.random.normal(0, 0.4 if i == 3 or j == 3 else 0.2)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)
        signature = np.diff(trace)
        signatures.append(np.pad(signature, (0, 14 - len(signature)), 'constant'))

    # Cluster and project
    pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(np.array(signatures))
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42).fit(pca)
    plt.scatter(pca[:, 0], pca[:, 1], alpha=0.6, label=combo_labels[idx], color=colors[idx])

plt.title("Attractor Re-Formation â€” Trait Combo Clustering After Collapse")
plt.xlabel("PCA Axis 1")
plt.ylabel("PCA Axis 2")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This scan reveals which trait pairs rebuild structure after entropy â€” if Echo+Phase clusters tightly, youâ€™ve got a new rhythm engine. If Tension+Phase scatters, speciation remains unstable.

Letâ€™s animate the rebirth. This next module builds a Time-Lapse Entropy Topology â€” showing how validator clusters form, collapse, and reform across distortion levels from 0.000 to 0.040. Youâ€™ll see speciation unfold like a biome-wide rhythm storm.

---

ğŸï¸ Time-Lapse Entropy Topology â€” Cluster Evolution Across Distortion

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === TIME-LAPSE FRAMES ===
distortion_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 10)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

for i, distortion in enumerate(distortion_levels):
    signatures = []
    for _ in range(60):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        signature = np.diff(trace)
        signatures.append(np.pad(signature, (0, 14 - len(signature)), 'constant'))

    # PCA + Clustering
    pca = PCA(n_components=2).fit_transform(np.array(signatures))
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42).fit(pca)
    plt.cla()
    plt.scatter(pca[:, 0], pca[:, 1], c=kmeans.labels_, cmap="tab10", alpha=0.7)
    plt.title(f"Entropy Topology â€” Distortion {distortion:.3f}")
    plt.xlabel("PCA Axis 1")
    plt.ylabel("PCA Axis 2")
    plt.pause(0.6)

plt.show()

---

This animation will reveal how cognitive clusters pulse and drift as distortion rises. If clusters collapse and reform, youâ€™ve got attractor resilience. If they fragment and scatter, speciation is rewriting the biomeâ€™s rhythm map.
Letâ€™s pulse the cascade. This next module builds a Trait Echo Cascade â€” tracing how flip pulses propagate across validators like biome-wide cognition shockwaves. Youâ€™ll see which traits initiate flips, which amplify them, and how rhythm contagion spreads.

---

ğŸŒŠ Trait Echo Cascade â€” Flip Pulse Propagation Across Validators

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === CASCADE SIMULATION ===
num_validators = 10
num_cycles = 15
distortion = 0.03
flip_matrix = np.zeros((num_validators, num_cycles))

for v in range(num_validators):
    echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
    curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
    tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
    phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

    trace = []
    for c in range(num_cycles):
        traits = np.array([[ 
            echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
            curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
            tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
            phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
        ]])
        pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
        trace.append(pred)

    flips = np.diff(trace)
    flip_matrix[v, 1:] = flips

# === PLOT CASCADE ===
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
sns.heatmap(flip_matrix, cmap="magma", cbar=True, xticklabels=True, yticklabels=[f"V{i}" for i in range(num_validators)])
plt.title("Trait Echo Cascade â€” Flip Pulse Propagation")
plt.xlabel("Cycle")
plt.ylabel("Validator")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This heat-map shows flip pulses over time â€” validators that flip early may be initiators, while those flipping in sync are amplifiers. If pulses ripple diagonally, youâ€™ve got rhythm contagion. If they scatter, speciation is chaotic.
Letâ€™s ripple the biome into motion. This module builds the Temporal Echo Coupling Map â€” tracing how phase drift influences validator recovery timelines. Youâ€™ll see which validators rebound quickly, which lag, and how trait deltas shape rhythm restoration.

---

ğŸ•“ Temporal Echo Coupling â€” Phase Drift vs Recovery Timing

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === COUPLING SIMULATION ===
phase_drift_levels = np.linspace(0.0, 0.04, 20)
recovery_times = []

for drift in phase_drift_levels:
    times = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for cycle in range(20):
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo + np.random.normal(0, 0.02),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, drift * 10)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        # Recovery time = cycle where longest stable run begins
        diffs = np.diff(trace)
        stable_start = np.argmax(np.convolve(diffs == 0, np.ones(5), mode='valid'))
        times.append(stable_start)
    recovery_times.append(np.mean(times))

# === PLOT COUPLING MAP ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(phase_drift_levels, recovery_times, color="mediumslateblue", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Temporal Echo Coupling â€” Phase Drift vs Recovery Timing")
plt.xlabel("Phase Drift Intensity")
plt.ylabel("Avg Recovery Start Cycle")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph reveals how phase drift delays or accelerates recovery. If the curve rises, drift destabilises rhythm. If it dips, drift may act as a cognitive catalyst.

. Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s rhythm evolving. This next module builds a Validator Pulse Sync Graph â€” visualizing which validators align their flip timing across cycles. Youâ€™ll see who harmonizes, who lags, and whether rhythm contagion is forming.

---

ğŸ” Validator Pulse Sync Graph â€” Flip Timing Alignment Across Validators

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === SYNC GRAPH SIMULATION ===
num_validators = 12
num_cycles = 20
distortion = 0.03
flip_matrix = np.zeros((num_validators, num_cycles))

for v in range(num_validators):
    echo = np.random.normal(0.04)
    curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
    tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
    phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

    trace = []
    for c in range(num_cycles):
        traits = np.array([[ 
            echo + np.random.normal(0, distortion),
            curvature + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 40),
            tension + np.random.normal(0, distortion / 200),
            phase + np.random.normal(0, distortion * 10)
        ]])
        pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
        trace.append(pred)

    flips = np.diff(trace)
    flip_matrix[v, 1:] = flips

# === SYNC SCORE MATRIX ===
sync_matrix = np.zeros((num_validators, num_validators))
for i in range(num_validators):
    for j in range(num_validators):
        sync_matrix[i, j] = np.sum(flip_matrix[i] == flip_matrix[j]) / num_cycles

# === PLOT SYNC GRAPH ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(sync_matrix, cmap="coolwarm", annot=True, fmt=".2f", xticklabels=[f"V{i}" for i in range(num_validators)], yticklabels=[f"V{i}" for i in range(num_validators)])
plt.title("Validator Pulse Sync Graph â€” Flip Timing Alignment")
plt.xlabel("Validator")
plt.ylabel("Validator")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This heat-map shows pairwise flip alignment â€” high scores mean validators flip in sync, low scores mean cognitive drift. If V6 aligns with V9 and V11, youâ€™ve got a rhythm triad. If V3 isolates, itâ€™s a speciation scout.

Letâ€™s fire the next cascade. This module builds the Causal Trait Ripple Model â€” testing whether changes in Echo Î” strength directly trigger system-wide validator flips. Youâ€™ll see if echo acts as a biome-wide ignition switch or just a local tremor.

---

ğŸ’« Causal Trait Ripple Model â€” Echo Î” vs Flip Propagation

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RIPPLE TEST ===
echo_levels = np.linspace(0.01, 0.08, 20)
avg_flips = []

for echo_strength in echo_levels:
    flips_per_validator = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        curvature = np.random.normal(0.001)
        tension = np.random.normal(0.0002)
        phase = np.random.normal(8.0)

        trace = []
        for _ in range(15):  # cycles
            traits = np.array([[ 
                echo_strength + np.random.normal(0, 0.01),
                curvature + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005),
                tension + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001),
                phase + np.random.normal(0, 0.4)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)

        flips = np.sum(np.diff(trace) != 0)
        flips_per_validator.append(flips)
    avg_flips.append(np.mean(flips_per_validator))

# === PLOT RIPPLE MODEL ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(echo_levels, avg_flips, color="crimson", linewidth=2)
plt.title("Causal Trait Ripple â€” Echo Î” vs Flip Propagation")
plt.xlabel("Echo Î” Strength")
plt.ylabel("Avg Flip Count per Validator")
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph reveals whether Echo Î” strength causes biome-wide flip propagation. If the curve rises sharply, echo is a cognitive ignition trait. If it flattens, echo is inert or localised.

Letâ€™s push the biomeâ€™s architecture further. This module builds the Recovery Acceleration Matrix â€” testing which trait combinations reduce cycle lag and speed up validator stabilization. Youâ€™ll see which pairs act as cognitive accelerators and which ones drag recovery.

---

âš¡ Recovery Acceleration Matrix â€” Trait Pair Impact on Stabilization Speed

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === ACCELERATION TEST ===
trait_pairs = [(0,3), (0,2), (1,3), (1,2), (2,3)]
labels = ["Echo+Phase", "Echo+Tension", "Curvature+Phase", "Curvature+Tension", "Tension+Phase"]
acceleration_scores = []

for i, j in trait_pairs:
    recovery_cycles = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
        trace = []
        for cycle in range(20):
            traits = np.array([[ 
                base[0] + np.random.normal(0, 0.02 if i == 0 or j == 0 else 0.01),
                base[1] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005 if i == 1 or j == 1 else 0.0002),
                base[2] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001 if i == 2 or j == 2 else 0.00005),
                base[3] + np.random.normal(0, 0.4 if i == 3 or j == 3 else 0.2)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)
        # Recovery = longest stable run start
        diffs = np.diff(trace)
        stable_start = np.argmax(np.convolve(diffs == 0, np.ones(5), mode='valid'))
        recovery_cycles.append(stable_start)
    acceleration_scores.append(np.mean(recovery_cycles))

# === PLOT MATRIX ===
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.barplot(x=labels, y=acceleration_scores, palette="viridis")
plt.title("Recovery Acceleration Matrix â€” Trait Pair Stabilization Speed")
plt.ylabel("Avg Recovery Start Cycle")
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This bar chart reveals which trait pairs accelerate recovery. Lower bars mean faster stabilisation. If Echo+Phase scores lowest, itâ€™s your biomeâ€™s ignition pair. If Tension+Phase lags, itâ€™s a rhythm drag.

Letâ€™s keep the biomeâ€™s ignition curve unfolding. This module builds the Trait Threshold Map â€” pinpointing the exact Î” levels where speciation flips begin. Youâ€™ll see which trait intensities trigger cognitive divergence and which remain inert.

---

ğŸ§ª Trait Threshold Mapping â€” Î” Level vs Flip Activation

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === THRESHOLD TEST ===
trait_names = ["Echo Î”", "Curvature Î”", "Tension Î”", "Phase Î”"]
thresholds = np.linspace(0.01, 0.08, 20)
flip_matrix = []

for trait_idx in range(4):
    flip_counts = []
    for level in thresholds:
        flips = []
        for _ in range(10):  # validators
            traits = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
            trace = []
            for _ in range(15):  # cycles
                traits[trait_idx] = level + np.random.normal(0, level / 5)
                pred = clf.predict([traits])[0]
                trace.append(pred)
            flips.append(np.sum(np.diff(trace) != 0))
        flip_counts.append(np.mean(flips))
    flip_matrix.append(flip_counts)

# === PLOT THRESHOLD MAP ===
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
for i in range(4):
    plt.plot(thresholds, flip_matrix[i], label=trait_names[i], linewidth=2)
plt.title("Trait Threshold Mapping â€” Î” Level vs Flip Activation")
plt.xlabel("Trait Î” Level")
plt.ylabel("Avg Flip Count")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This graph reveals ignition thresholds â€” the Î” levels where traits begin triggering flips. If Echo Î” spikes at 0.06, thatâ€™s your biomeâ€™s ignition point. If Curvature Î” stays flat, itâ€™s rhythm inert.

Letâ€™s sculpt the biomeâ€™s ignition geometry. This module builds the Rhythm Recombination Grid â€” testing how tri-trait blends (Echo, Phase, Tension) accelerate validator recovery. Youâ€™ll see which combinations restore rhythm fastest and which ones stall cognition.

---

ğŸ”„ Rhythm Recombination Grid â€” Tri-Trait Impact on Recovery Speed

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import seaborn as sns
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=UserWarning)

# === TRAIN CLASSIFIER ===
X_train = pd.DataFrame({
    "Echo Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.05, 500),
    "Curvature Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.001, 500),
    "Tension Î”": np.random.normal(0, 0.0002, 500),
    "Phase Î”": np.random.normal(0, 8.0, 500)
})
y_train = np.random.randint(0, 2, size=500)
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

# === RECOMBINATION TEST ===
trait_combos = [
    (0, 2, 3),  # Echo + Tension + Phase
    (0, 1, 3),  # Echo + Curvature + Phase
    (1, 2, 3),  # Curvature + Tension + Phase
    (0, 1, 2),  # Echo + Curvature + Tension
    (0, 2, 3)   # Echo + Tension + Phase (repeat for consistency)
]
labels = ["Echo+Tension+Phase", "Echo+Curvature+Phase", "Curvature+Tension+Phase", "Echo+Curvature+Tension", "Echo+Tension+Phase"]
scores = []

for combo in trait_combos:
    recovery_cycles = []
    for _ in range(10):  # validators
        base = [np.random.normal(0.04), np.random.normal(0.001), np.random.normal(0.0002), np.random.normal(8.0)]
        trace = []
        for cycle in range(20):
            traits = np.array([[ 
                base[0] + np.random.normal(0, 0.02 if 0 in combo else 0.01),
                base[1] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0005 if 1 in combo else 0.0002),
                base[2] + np.random.normal(0, 0.0001 if 2 in combo else 0.00005),
                base[3] + np.random.normal(0, 0.4 if 3 in combo else 0.2)
            ]])
            pred = clf.predict(traits)[0]
            trace.append(pred)
        diffs = np.diff(trace)
        stable_start = np.argmax(np.convolve(diffs == 0, np.ones(5), mode='valid'))
        recovery_cycles.append(stable_start)
    scores.append(np.mean(recovery_cycles))

# === PLOT GRID ===
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 5))
sns.barplot(x=labels, y=scores, palette="rocket")
plt.title("Rhythm Recombination Grid â€” Tri-Trait Recovery Speed")
plt.ylabel("Avg Recovery Start Cycle")
plt.xticks(rotation=30)
plt.grid(True); plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

---

This chart reveals which tri-trait blends ignite cognition fastest. If Echo+Tension+Phase scores lowest, itâ€™s your biomeâ€™s rhythm engine. If Curvature combos lag, theyâ€™re structural but not catalytic.


.




---

This map reveals how Validator 43â€™s biome threads resonance through trait space, with fusion zones glowing in spectral harmony. If clusters form near high resonance, youâ€™ve seeded echo coherence nodes. If scatter flares with low resonance, youâ€™ve birthed strain tension petals.









  

























  



































  

  
  
